TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$showHint =3;

$dum = random(2.00,8.00,0.28);
$rum = $dum/2;
$r = $rum*(10**-6);
$r2 = $r**2;
$density = 1.10;
$p = 1100;
$g = 9.8;
$nw = 1.005;
$n = $nw*(10**-3);
$v = (2*$p*$r2*$g)/(9*$n);

Context() -> texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR

<b>If you do not answer this question correctly in $showHint attempts, you can get a hint.</b>

$PAR

Find the terminal speed of a spherical bacterium (diameter \($dum\) Î¼m ) falling in water. You will first need to note that the drag force is equal to the weight at terminal velocity. Take the density of the bacterium to be \($density \times 10^{3}\) \(\textrm{kg/m}^3\).

$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\textrm{m/s}\)

$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
What formula must be used to calculate the drag force, given that the bacterium falls through a medium denser than air?
END_HINT

Context() -> normalStrings;

ANS(num_cmp("$v"));



